<para id="element-62">
<exercise id="exercise-62">
<problem id="idm3733952">
<para id="element-63">A circular body of mass “M” and radius “R” rolls inside a hemispherical shell of radius “R”. It is released from the top edge of the hemisphere.  Then, the angular kinetic energy at the bottom of the shell is maximum, if the circular body is :
</para>
<para id="element-64">
<m:math display="block">
<m:mtable columnalign="left">
<m:mtr>
<m:mtd>
<m:mi> (a) </m:mi>
 <m:mspace width="4pt"/>
<m:mtext> a ring 
 </m:mtext>
<m:mspace width="4pt"/>
<m:mi> (b) </m:mi>
<m:mspace width="4pt"/>
<m:mtext> a disk
 </m:mtext>
<m:mspace width="4pt"/>
<m:mi> (c) </m:mi>
<m:mspace width="4pt"/>
<m:mtext> a hollow sphere
 </m:mtext>
<m:mspace width="4pt"/>
<m:mi> (d) </m:mi>
<m:mspace width="4pt"/>
<m:mtext> a solid sphere
 </m:mtext>
</m:mtd>
</m:mtr>
</m:mtable>
</m:math>
</para>
</problem>
<solution id="idm6741856">

<para id="element-65">
Since mechanical energy is conserved in rolling, the total kinetic energy for a circular body is a constant. Now, ratio of translational and rotational kinetic energy is :
</para>
<para id="element-66">
<m:math display="block">
<m:mtable columnalign="left">
<m:mtr>
<m:mtd>
<m:mfrac>
<m:mrow>
<m:msub>
<m:mi> K </m:mi>
<m:mi> T </m:mi>
</m:msub>
</m:mrow>
<m:mrow>
<m:msub>
<m:mi> K </m:mi>
<m:mi> R </m:mi>
</m:msub>
</m:mrow>
</m:mfrac>
<m:mo> = </m:mo> 
<m:mfrac>
<m:mrow>
<m:mi> M </m:mi>
<m:msup>
<m:mi> R </m:mi>
<m:mn> 2 </m:mn>
</m:msup>
</m:mrow>
<m:mrow>
<m:mi> I </m:mi>
</m:mrow>
</m:mfrac>
</m:mtd>
</m:mtr>
</m:mtable>
</m:math>
</para>
<para id="element-67">
This ratio is independent of the position of the rolling body. Thus, rotational kinetic energy (and hence angular velocity) is maximum for the circular body having maximum moment of inertia. Here, ring for same mass and radius has the maximum moment of inertia. As such, angular velocity is maximum for the ring.
</para>
<para id="element-68">
Hence, option (a) is correct.
</para>
</solution>
</exercise>
</para>

